+Feature: Missing seam coverage
+
+  The following scenarios are non-binding scenarios written by the Shipwright
+  role during harbour fitting-out. They are not QM targets. Captain reads them
+  to decide whether to promote any to binding scenarios, to refine existing ones,
+  or to discard as low worth.
+
+  @captain
+  Scenario: Empty tide table returns an error
+    Given an empty tide table
+    When I ask for the next high tide after "2026-07-12T05:00:00Z"
+    Then the prediction fails with "no upcoming high tide in data"
+
+  @captain
+  Scenario: Multiple high tides returns the chronologically next
+    Given the tide table for Fundy Cove
+    When I ask for the next high tide after "2026-07-12T05:00:00Z"
+    Then the predicted high tide is at "2026-07-12T16:45:00Z" with height 4.5
+    # Plank gap: current step hardcodes the data source — when the data
+    # shape changes (more stations, extra tides) the single assertion
+    # still passes but the chronology invariant is no longer tested
+    # because every tide row is fixed. A captain-tagged faster form:
+    #   Given a tide table with multiple highs before and after a pivot
+    #   When I ask for the next high after {time}
+    #   Then the returned tide is the earliest high with time > {time}
+
+  @captain
+  Scenario: Boundary — pivot exactly on a high tide
+    Given the tide table for Fundy Cove
+    When I ask for the next high tide after "2026-07-12T16:45:00Z"
+    Then the prediction fails with "no upcoming high tide in data"
+    # Plank gap: the implementation uses strict greater-than
+    # (new Date(t.time) > new Date(after)), so a pivot equal to a high
+    # tide correctly skips it. This behaviour is NOT tested by the current
+    # scenarios and should be captured.
+
+  @captain
+  Scenario: Only low tides in data returns an error
+    Given a tide table with no high tides
+    When I ask for the next high tide after "2026-07-12T05:00:00Z"
+    Then the prediction fails with "no upcoming high tide in data"
+    # Plank gap: no scenario verifies that the function correctly
+    # rejects data that has tides but no high-tide rows.
+
+  @captain
+  Scenario: Stations data is loaded for product use
+    Given the station data for Fundy Cove
+    When the system uses the station data
+    Then the station data is available for tide calculations
+    # Plank gap: data/stations.json exists with 120 stations but is never
+    # read by production code or exercised by any scenario. Either it is
+    # dead data (report-only finding), or it should be plumbed into the
+    # product — Captain decides.
